The bottom width is in proportion, but the top is a little too wide.  The knob projects too far above the top of the lid, and the spout extends a little too far from the side of the teapot.  Did you notice that the bottom of the handle is a little thicker than the upper part?

The guidelines for the sides of the teapot have been drawn by the method of addition rather than the method of reduction.  There are no visible guidelines for the spout.  Perhaps they were not captured during scanning.  However, the spout is drawn in fairly good proportion, although the underside is not as curved as drawn.  The same is true of the top of the lid and the bottom of the teapot.  The right hand side of the teapot is not as straight as drawn.

A much better teapot would have been produced if you started by marking on a strip of paper the total height, bottom width, top width, lid height and how much the spout and handle extend out from the sides of Prof. Kang's teapot.  Estimating or calculating the proportions of these measurements to the height or width of his teapot would have avoided the problem referred to above.  Drawing a straight line through the two ends of a curve makes drawing the curve much easier and more accurate.

The guidelines are sparse and do not help in drawing the details, particularly the curves.  The sides of the teapot are drawn straight, not curved, but the underside of the spout and the top of the lid are drawn too curved.  The bottom should curve sharply at the corners, but not so much in the middle.  The top and bottom parts of the handle slope up far too steeply, making the handle look too long.

It is a pity that failure to check the relative dimensions of the outer and inner squares before proceeding to draw the circles and arcs has spoiled what would otherwise have been a very good sketch.

上方的兩個深度線沒有與下方的兩個深度線平行.

The guidelines are all shown and indicate that the square method has been correctly used.  Diagonal lines would have been extra help, and may have provided a warning that the smaller squares are not all of an equal size.  The outer square has not been divided equally in half, which affects the proportions of the two arcs.

The outer circle, arcs and small circles have all been drawn as intended.  However, the outer circle is slightly oval because the length of its guideline square is a little longer than its width.  The two arcs are not of the same length because the two halves of the outer guideline square are not equal.

In preparation for an exercise like this try drawing a square and divide it into four equal parts.  Take a ruler and check that the four sides of each square are of equal length.  Check that the corners all look like right angles.  Practise this repeatedly until you have trained your eye to divide a line accurately in half and can draw lines at right angles to each other.\\nThen place a rice bowl upside down on the paper and draw around its circumference.  Remove the\\nbowl and practise tracing around the circle you have drawn.  This will give you the feel of drawing circles.  Draw a square around the circle and look at how the circle meets the sides of the square and touches them.  Try tracing your circle by drawing short arcs either side of each of the four tangent points and then filling in the gaps between each of the arcs.  It is easier drawing a dotted line at first rather than a solid line.\\nI hope this will be of help.
